prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: faintest galaxies: 2-5 mJy
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We propose to observe with ALMA the CO[2-1] emission redshifted to the band 4 in a highy complete (in stellar mass and SFR) sample of 66 galaxies in a very narrow redshift range (0.72 < z < 0.74) in GOODS-S.In order to limit the exposure time, we group the galaxy per bin of CO[2-1] flux in several Science Goals in order to set the sensitivity at different vaules and obtain a similar S/N at different fluxes. In this Science Goal we target the group of the faintest galaxies in our sample with predicted Co[2-1] flux density between 2 and 5 mJy.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The Co[2-1] emission line has a width of 300 km/s or larger (Carilli & Walker 2013). A bandwith of 4226 km/s with a resolution of ~70 km/s will allow us to have more than 3 elements to fully resolve the line. This correlator set-up does not allow further averaging of the data rate.

This pilot project aim to obtainining the integrated CO emission of each galaxies. Thus, we treat our sources as point source and we request a minimum spatial resolution of 2 arcsec. We have no interest in larger scale emission. We reserve the study the resolved CO maps to a future project.

A first guess of the CO[2-1] flux density is estimated by using the SFR-H_2 mass correlation of Tacconi et al. 2013 to estimate the molecular mass at the galaxy redshift and then the relation of Solomon et al. (1997) to estimate the CO[2-1] flux density from the molecular mass at the observed frequency and assuming a line width of 300 km/s. The rms is set to reach a S/N~5 of the CO[2-1] emission of the faintest point source in the galaxy list provided for the Science Goal. Consequently a S/N well above 5 will be reached for the CO detection of the remaining galaxies with higher CO fluxes. We selected a bandwidth of 1875 Mhz (~4220 km/s) at the lowest resolution of 32 Mhz (70 km/s). We use the representative window resolution of ~32 Mhz (~70 km/s) for the sensitivity calculation. This choice is dictated by the need to fully resolve the line and study its shape. This will allow us to check for the presence of molecular gas outflow in particular among the AGNs included in our sample (Brusa et al 2015).
Our spectral setup leads to the use of only one spectral window into one baseband for the CO[2-1] detection. To make an efficient use of the second baseband, we observe the continuum at 145 GHz in the same correlator-setup. Though obtaining the continuum is not the main goal of the proposal, we will use such information, when the S/N will allow, to estimate the galaxy SFR to compare with the mid and far-infrared estimate.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The star formation activity in a galaxy is regulated by the availability of the molecular gas to form stars. Understanding how the molecular gas content evolves in galaxies is mandatory to understand the evolution of the cosmic star formation activity. The main goal of the proposed project is to measure with ALMA the integrated CO[2-1] emission to estimate the molecular gas mass in a sample of 66 galaxies in the GOODS-S region in a very narrow redshift range 0.72 < z < 0.74. Such window host a long filamentary structure encompassing a comprehensive range of environments (group, filament, field) . The galaxy sample spans a very large range in SFR and stellar masses and in environments. The purpose is to measure the molecular gas mass function and the molecular mass density at intermediate redshift between the COLDGASS value at $z\sim 0$ and the PHIBBS value at z~ 1.5- 2. Even more, we will be able to connect the evolution of the galaxy cold gas content to the galaxy host halo mass and follow the H_2 mass fraction-host halo mass relation from z~0 (COLDGASS) to z~0.73.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
